{
  "texts": [
    "Which brings us to another difficult question; what is consciousness?",
    "Seeking the lexicological origins of the term, one must explore the abysmal depths of Ancient Greek literature to find the world suneidésis, \"Συνείδησις\" (< συν -(σύν) + εἴδησις < οἶδα), the essence of which means \"together < we > + know\".",
    "The Latin descendant was translated as \"conscientia\" which was used in modern times by René Descartes and later John Locke for creating the word \"consciousness\" [10].",
    "But here comes a condradiction.",
    "It was Descartes who conceived the famous aphorism, \"Cogito, ergo sum\", or \"I think, therefore I am\"."
  ]
}